117
00:07:27,346 --> 00:07:28,087
need for speed game.

118
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,661
And we wanted to keep it simple, so we drew inspiration from the

119
00:07:31,701 --> 00:07:36,182
original 3DO Need for Speeds. Exotic cars. This was the first

120
00:07:36,222 --> 00:07:39,143
time we had licensed cars, and we really wanted to celebrate

121
00:07:39,163 --> 00:07:42,764
the heritage of those cars. And also, it was the first time we

122
00:07:42,804 --> 00:07:45,805
were working with the data from manufacturers, and we kept true

123
00:07:45,825 --> 00:07:49,586
to that. So we redid our physics model, we redid our handling

124
00:07:49,606 --> 00:07:51,727
model. We did it again and again and again until we had it

125
00:07:51,767 --> 00:07:54,327
perfect so we could take all of those torque curves, take all of

126
00:07:54,387 --> 00:07:56,588
those aerodynamic coefficients and all that good physics-y

127
00:07:56,608 --> 00:07:56,748
stuff.

128
00:07:58,937 --> 00:08:02,217
and have the accurate, not 60 times, have the accurate top speeds.

129
00:08:02,818 --> 00:08:04,078
In fact, when we were making the game,

130
00:08:04,598 --> 00:08:08,259
there was a point in development where I think it was the Mercedes SLS,

131
00:08:09,039 --> 00:08:10,720
it was sort of five miles an hour above

132
00:08:11,380 --> 00:08:13,161
the actual quoted top speed.

133
00:08:14,561 --> 00:08:16,662
And we were scratching our heads a bit and then we realized that

134
00:08:17,122 --> 00:08:21,063
the CAD model, the tires on it, were slightly wrong, they were the wrong wheels.

135
00:08:21,643 --> 00:08:25,444
And just that tiny little difference made that difference in the simulation.

136
00:08:26,932 --> 00:08:30,893
It's good to just have that data and be true to that because it's a really nice physical

137
00:08:30,913 --> 00:08:31,814
underpinning to your cars.

138
00:08:32,994 --> 00:08:34,734
And then the next was Epic Drives.

139
00:08:35,535 --> 00:08:40,616
So our ambition was to make a world that was stitched together from all the best of the

140
00:08:40,856 --> 00:08:42,817
epic West Coast drives that there are here in the US.

141
00:08:43,577 --> 00:08:49,038
So that was stitched together with these huge big vistas and every time you came around

142
00:08:49,078 --> 00:08:51,659
a corner we tried to put as many big vistas in the game as possible.

143
00:08:52,099 --> 00:08:53,280
Whether it be a mountain vista.

144
00:08:53,915 --> 00:08:59,777
A big open stretch of desert, these gorgeous stretches of coastal highway where you suddenly

145
00:08:59,817 --> 00:09:00,937
see a big bridge or something.

146
00:09:02,277 --> 00:09:07,819
But then also stretches of rural areas and farmland, and then giant redwood forest.

147
00:09:09,719 --> 00:09:11,180
Then our third pillar players the cops.

148
00:09:11,900 --> 00:09:16,041
Advanced weaponry, battling, high speed pursuits felt like this was a great opportunity for

149
00:09:16,081 --> 00:09:18,022
us to get our Criterion spectacle into the game.

150
00:09:20,892 --> 00:09:23,353
When we had these things, we just slather over the top of it,

151
00:09:23,533 --> 00:09:24,594
Criterion Special Source.

152
00:09:25,554 --> 00:09:26,915
This is what Criterion's known for.

153
00:09:27,755 --> 00:09:31,217
As I said before, we're an arcade racing game studio,

154
00:09:31,517 --> 00:09:34,778
and we've got a great heritage of arcade races through Burnout.

155
00:09:35,398 --> 00:09:37,539
And these are underpinned by spectacular physics,

156
00:09:38,344 --> 00:09:41,547
But also we always try and have accessible handling over the top of this.

157
00:09:42,208 --> 00:09:44,710
So as well as boost, we've got responsive controls.

158
00:09:45,010 --> 00:09:47,092
And the world was made with these long sweeping turns.

159
00:09:47,112 --> 00:09:52,197
So actually that road network, a lot of time goes into the angle of those turns,

160
00:09:52,217 --> 00:09:53,298
the angle of all those corners.

161
00:09:53,958 --> 00:09:54,419
And, um...

162
00:09:55,371 --> 00:09:58,692
In terms of having intuitive drift, it's not a drift button.

163
00:09:59,072 --> 00:10:01,052
You can either tap the brake, you can hold the brake,

164
00:10:01,072 --> 00:10:03,193
you can tap the e-brake, all of these different ways

165
00:10:03,293 --> 00:10:05,393
so that whatever the player's intent is,

166
00:10:05,833 --> 00:10:07,474
we can pick that up in the game

167
00:10:07,794 --> 00:10:10,154
and translate that into the drift that you want to see.

168
00:10:11,715 --> 00:10:14,555
Then, crashing, sense of speed, intensity.

169
00:10:15,415 --> 00:10:18,656
Cinematic spectacle is where Criterion really feels at home.

170
00:10:19,476 --> 00:10:21,717
And from our previous games, from Burnout, from Black,

171
00:10:22,077 --> 00:10:23,657
we know how to craft these experiences.

