00:10:32,747 --> 00:10:35,568
So Burnout 3 was when we started experimenting with this.

175
00:10:35,688 --> 00:10:37,349
It was EA's first online title.

176
00:10:37,969 --> 00:10:44,331
And then Burnout Paradise, this is where we really pushed our open world to be able to

177
00:10:44,391 --> 00:10:46,692
have that seamless online.

178
00:10:46,732 --> 00:10:50,334
So you could jump into a game, jump into a friends game, then matchmake into a public

179
00:10:50,354 --> 00:10:53,315
game all without leaving the world and constantly driving around.

180
00:10:54,012 --> 00:10:57,539
And we started really beginning to experiment in that year of Paradise when we were developing

181
00:10:57,600 --> 00:11:01,849
Free Burn Challenges, which for our Burnout Paradise fans, that still stands as some of

182
00:11:01,869 --> 00:11:03,031
the best card play you can have.

183
00:11:06,729 --> 00:11:15,732
But this friends at the heart of the game, it's not a solved problem, but we know that it's really important to us because when you're playing a game with friends, then that makes the game endless.

184
00:11:15,812 --> 00:11:24,094
Your game becomes a vehicle for your friends to get together and hang out and interact together and just have those interactions between real people and real people.

185
00:11:24,334 --> 00:11:28,656
Gamers are social people and having those interactions with friends that you can attribute.

186
00:11:31,093 --> 00:11:34,235
that you can attribute those actions to a real person

187
00:11:34,856 --> 00:11:37,878
just makes it a lot more interesting, a lot more meaningful

188
00:11:38,518 --> 00:11:39,559
and it makes it more memorable.

189
00:11:40,199 --> 00:11:42,961
And then those interactions and that fun that you have in the game

190
00:11:43,461 --> 00:11:45,662
that can spill over into your real world conversations.

191
00:11:46,503 --> 00:11:48,144
And in that way the game just grows and grows

192
00:11:48,324 --> 00:11:50,846
and becomes a really great experience to share.

193
00:11:53,807 --> 00:11:56,609
But then the problem with trying to get real friends into a game together

194
00:11:56,669 --> 00:11:57,310
especially back in 2009

195
00:11:59,017 --> 00:12:00,478
Real friends lead real lives.

196
00:12:00,959 --> 00:12:02,299
And it's really hard to coordinate

197
00:12:02,460 --> 00:12:03,640
to get online at the same time.

198
00:12:05,782 --> 00:12:08,604
It's hard enough to get colleagues out to the pub

199
00:12:08,664 --> 00:12:11,246
after work on a Friday night, let alone everyone

200
00:12:11,306 --> 00:12:14,448
online at the same time with the same game when they're at home.

201
00:12:18,350 --> 00:12:20,372
And so this is something we actually

