00:13:19,505 --> 00:13:23,447
We really thought rather than trying to push players into online multiplayer, how can we

220
00:13:23,487 --> 00:13:27,608
create these meaningful and ongoing social play experiences for those millions of players

221
00:13:27,628 --> 00:13:30,450
that are connected but don't want to play online against others.

222
00:13:31,450 --> 00:13:35,692
So this felt like a really great opportunity to create play with friends using asynchronous

223
00:13:35,732 --> 00:13:36,152
interaction.

224
00:13:38,753 --> 00:13:43,896
So just to recap, synchronous, that's a phone call, asynchronous, that's a text message.

225
00:13:45,422 --> 00:13:47,883
But the thing that's great about asynchronous,

226
00:13:48,463 --> 00:13:50,123
it's things like broadcasting.

227
00:13:50,143 --> 00:13:51,444
You know, you get notifications.

228
00:13:52,304 --> 00:13:54,445
Twitter, Facebook, and WhatsApp, these

229
00:13:54,565 --> 00:13:57,907
are communication tools that allow people to share much more

230
00:13:58,247 --> 00:14:01,888
with more friends, regardless of living different lives.

231
00:14:03,209 --> 00:14:05,009
And this felt like a real opportunity for the game,

232
00:14:05,470 --> 00:14:07,370
the space in which we could innovate and bring friends

233
00:14:07,410 --> 00:14:10,712
together by focusing on those asynchronous interactions.

234
00:14:12,032 --> 00:14:13,693
And then we could really make it about real friends.

235
00:14:17,605 --> 00:14:26,234
So just to put your minds back to 2009, this was when we started making the game.

236
00:14:29,377 --> 00:14:36,744
So in 2009, there's a picture of Xbox Live at that point, or of the dashboard, and it

