00:15:01,959 --> 00:15:03,621
And they were now mature, because Facebook had been

245
00:15:03,641 --> 00:15:04,802
around for a few years at that point.

246
00:15:05,562 --> 00:15:08,185
And so we wanted all of these things that you had on

247
00:15:08,225 --> 00:15:10,066
Facebook and on other social networks.

248
00:15:10,827 --> 00:15:13,069
So we wanted to be able to find friends of friends, to be

249
00:15:13,109 --> 00:15:15,911
able to grow our friends network by seeing what friends

250
00:15:15,951 --> 00:15:18,774
of friends had got up to, and also to just have those things

251
00:15:18,814 --> 00:15:21,876
like sharing, like commenting, like profile pictures, which

252
00:15:21,896 --> 00:15:23,498
we now just have built into our consoles

253
00:15:23,538 --> 00:15:24,178
and take for granted.

254
00:15:26,978 --> 00:15:28,159
So that was step one.

255
00:15:28,920 --> 00:15:32,943
Step one for our social play for Hot Pursuit,

256
00:15:33,484 --> 00:15:34,785
we didn't quite know what we were making.

257
00:15:34,925 --> 00:15:36,967
But the first thing was, hey, let's build a website.

258
00:15:37,587 --> 00:15:39,128
And then we're going to build a web browser

259
00:15:39,389 --> 00:15:40,349
and put that into our game.

260
00:15:40,810 --> 00:15:43,732
And that website in the game, that was our game front end.

261
00:15:44,593 --> 00:15:48,216
And then, hey, that was the year I got a smartphone

262
00:15:48,236 --> 00:15:48,836
for the first time.

263
00:15:48,876 --> 00:15:50,137
And that felt really cool and exciting.

264
00:15:50,177 --> 00:15:51,919
I could put that website on my smartphone.

265
00:15:51,959 --> 00:15:54,241
It was the same website in the game as out of the game.

266
00:15:55,041 --> 00:15:55,161
So.

267
00:15:56,604 --> 00:15:58,425
It felt very new and exciting and different.

268
00:15:59,526 --> 00:16:01,588
But the other thing that we learned very quickly was that

269
00:16:02,129 --> 00:16:05,352
actually working in web for a front end is really powerful

270
00:16:05,392 --> 00:16:08,815
because that rapid iteration speed that you get with web is

271
00:16:08,855 --> 00:16:11,017
just worlds ahead because there's no build time.

272
00:16:11,158 --> 00:16:12,419
You're not waiting for anything.

273
00:16:12,999 --> 00:16:15,662
It's just you make a change and you see it straight away.

274
00:16:16,343 --> 00:16:18,465
So we could try out lots of ideas very, very quickly.

275
00:16:19,666 --> 00:16:21,047
So it meant it was great for discovery.

276
00:16:23,497 --> 00:16:27,039
But then the problem with this is this is not a console UX

277
00:16:27,079 --> 00:16:27,600
experience.

278
00:16:28,220 --> 00:16:31,662
And text entry, that's a problem for trying

279
00:16:31,682 --> 00:16:32,823
to make these social features.

280
00:16:33,724 --> 00:16:35,365
So writing out comments and posts

281
00:16:36,246 --> 00:16:37,787
using an on-screen keyboard, that's

282
00:16:37,847 --> 00:16:39,568
no way to spend precious console time.

283
00:16:43,090 --> 00:16:45,252
So version 2, this is what we really got to.

284
00:16:46,313 --> 00:16:47,413
This was the exciting part.

285
00:16:48,114 --> 00:16:49,715
We automatically generated stories.

286
00:16:49,735 --> 00:16:50,876
We did the work for the player.

287
00:16:51,815 --> 00:16:54,418
and it worked. It gave people a real sense of playing with other people.

288
00:16:55,619 --> 00:16:59,542
The game had to track everything, and all of these actions became human stories,

289
00:17:00,723 --> 00:17:02,865
and they were then shared back to me and my friends,

290
00:17:04,667 --> 00:17:06,789
and it became the way you played the game.

291
00:17:07,317 --> 00:17:08,798
there was a feed for every game mode.

292
00:17:09,498 --> 00:17:11,079
And so there was no longer an event list,

293
00:17:11,139 --> 00:17:14,400
there was no set way of playing through the events.

294
00:17:14,440 --> 00:17:16,560
You just played the events that were based

295
00:17:16,620 --> 00:17:17,541
on what your friends played.

296
00:17:17,881 --> 00:17:19,361
And so you got a sense of what was popular.

297
00:17:20,002 --> 00:17:21,382
And playing the events became this sort of

298
00:17:21,562 --> 00:17:23,183
back and forth conversation with your friends.

299
00:17:24,863 --> 00:17:26,244
But the real promise there came from

300
00:17:26,284 --> 00:17:28,145
when we started tracking leaderboard changes.

301
00:17:28,825 --> 00:17:30,425
And then we could build these stories

302
00:17:30,485 --> 00:17:31,666
from those leaderboard changes

303
00:17:31,726 --> 00:17:32,946
to make them as rich as possible.

304
00:17:33,747 --> 00:17:35,547
And also, it's that point of

305
00:17:36,149 --> 00:17:39,790
Rather than just showing a leaderboard, you really, by writing a story about it, you're

306
00:17:39,810 --> 00:17:43,071
really focusing in on where that player is on the leaderboard and what they need to do

307
00:17:43,172 --> 00:17:44,292
to take that next position.

308
00:17:44,372 --> 00:17:47,973
So just break down that task of getting to the top of the leaderboard into one step at

309
00:17:48,013 --> 00:17:48,313
a time.

310
00:17:51,154 --> 00:17:54,095
The other thing we had was a call to action.

311
00:17:54,235 --> 00:18:00,758
So at every single opportunity throughout this website front end that was the first

312
00:18:00,798 --> 00:18:01,478
version of Autolog.

313
00:18:02,856 --> 00:18:05,498
We gave people the opportunity to jump straight into the game,

314
00:18:05,558 --> 00:18:06,859
to play what was being talked about,

315
00:18:06,899 --> 00:18:08,720
to play what was posted to a photo feed,

316
00:18:09,700 --> 00:18:11,862
to play what was talked about on the wall.

317
00:18:12,862 --> 00:18:15,044
And we put these call-to-actions at all points.

318
00:18:16,064 --> 00:18:17,405
So wherever you were in the game,

319
00:18:17,445 --> 00:18:19,186
you could just jump straight to the event and play it.

320
00:18:19,667 --> 00:18:21,888
And that, to us, felt really, really interesting at the time

321
00:18:22,108 --> 00:18:25,570
because it meant that it was totally dynamic.

322
00:18:25,630 --> 00:18:27,391
Whatever I was playing, whatever I was being fed

323
00:18:27,752 --> 00:18:30,253
was what the game told me about through this social network,

324
00:18:30,473 --> 00:18:31,494
through what my friends were doing.

325
00:18:34,595 --> 00:18:38,237
To show an example of that, here was our rapid response feed at the time.

326
00:18:39,378 --> 00:18:45,562
So those events were recorded and every action was tracked and then a comparison was made

327
00:18:45,622 --> 00:18:48,684
for every single time one of your friends attempted the event.

328
00:18:50,405 --> 00:18:53,868
And so yeah, as I said, there was a feed per event type split by cop or racer.

329
00:18:55,449 --> 00:18:56,870
And that was the main way to play the game.

330
00:18:57,950 --> 00:19:00,732
So if your friend tried an event, it was in your feed ready for you to try.

331
00:19:03,417 --> 00:19:04,959
And at that point, we were like, excellent.

332
00:19:05,199 --> 00:19:06,400
Now you're really feeling like you're

333
00:19:06,420 --> 00:19:08,523
playing with your friends whenever you played the game.

334
00:19:10,425 --> 00:19:15,210
But the problem with this was need for speed social.

335
00:19:15,250 --> 00:19:17,833
That doesn't sound like it might have been engaging.

336
00:19:17,873 --> 00:19:19,234
It was interesting.

337
00:19:19,274 --> 00:19:21,216
You got a real sense of what your friends were doing.

338
00:19:21,757 --> 00:19:23,979
And you could have taken that further to start.

339
00:19:25,597 --> 00:19:31,204
If you got into it, then you could really choose how you played and sort of set up your own progression with your friends.

340
00:19:32,145 --> 00:19:37,411
But ultimately it wasn't fun. It hadn't honed in on this on this core experience and.

341
00:19:38,770 --> 00:19:42,112
There was also this other problem of we've been building in web for a while now

342
00:19:42,552 --> 00:19:43,913
and we had really bad feature creep.

343
00:19:43,993 --> 00:19:46,635
We were writing checks that we wouldn't be able to cache in production

344
00:19:47,495 --> 00:19:48,636
because we had all these features.

345
00:19:48,676 --> 00:19:54,459
We had a timeline feature where all of your actions got amalgamated

346
00:19:54,519 --> 00:19:57,881
and aggregated into these timelines that you could compare against other players

347
00:19:58,581 --> 00:20:01,242
and we were just getting ahead of ourselves.

348
00:20:01,302 --> 00:20:03,924
We had all these multiple feeds and ways of managing those feeds,

349
00:20:04,004 --> 00:20:05,325
ways of looking at your friends' feeds.

350
00:20:06,418 --> 00:20:08,760
And really, we'd gone a bit too far with it.

351
00:20:09,821 --> 00:20:11,803
And that meant we had this terrible problem with signal

352
00:20:11,843 --> 00:20:13,924
to noise ratio, and it was really hiding

353
00:20:13,944 --> 00:20:14,585
the fun of the game.

354
00:20:16,286 --> 00:20:18,168
So what were we going to do?

355
00:20:18,288 --> 00:20:20,170
So this got us scratching our heads a bit.

356
00:20:20,910 --> 00:20:23,313
And the answer was in Beat It.

357
00:20:23,913 --> 00:20:28,557
So we were asking ourselves, how are these features in

358
00:20:28,597 --> 00:20:29,398
service to the game?

359
00:20:30,239 --> 00:20:33,221
And we took all of those automated feeds, and then we

360
00:20:33,762 --> 00:20:34,382
curated them.

361
00:20:35,618 --> 00:20:38,480
automatically to be one feed of recommendations.

362
00:20:39,161 --> 00:20:41,283
Because throughout the whole time of playing with your friends,

363
00:20:42,944 --> 00:20:46,447
it might seem obvious now, but the most compelling motivation,

364
00:20:46,828 --> 00:20:48,990
way beyond anything else, is someone beat you.

365
00:20:50,171 --> 00:20:52,453
Ultimately, when you look at popular events and things like that,

366
00:20:52,793 --> 00:20:54,194
they're just not as interesting because

367
00:20:54,775 --> 00:20:57,998
they don't change over time necessarily or...

368
00:20:58,658 --> 00:21:00,200
Yeah, whereas someone beat you, that means,

369
00:21:00,940 --> 00:21:03,022
hey, one of my friends, they've played my event and they're...

370
00:21:03,472 --> 00:21:07,834
They've beat me at it, but I didn't really try, so I can go back and I can beat them.

371
00:21:07,894 --> 00:21:09,595
I can beat that one faster.

372
00:21:10,616 --> 00:21:16,499
And it also made us change all of our events, because before that point, we also had events

373
00:21:16,599 --> 00:21:18,640
which were based on points.

374
00:21:19,941 --> 00:21:24,483
And we had a few different event modes, but if they didn't sort of...

375
00:21:25,382 --> 00:21:27,504
If they didn't support this idea of being the fastest,

376
00:21:28,164 --> 00:21:31,787
then they fell to the side because they weren't as engaging.

377
00:21:31,807 --> 00:21:33,889
They weren't as natural to talk about an event.

378
00:21:33,909 --> 00:21:35,250
You know, when you're comparing points,

379
00:21:35,790 --> 00:21:38,132
it's one step removed from this idea of be the fastest.

380
00:21:39,693 --> 00:21:41,575
And then we used all of these other rich stats

381
00:21:41,615 --> 00:21:44,197
and comparisons that we had and that we were generating.

382
00:21:45,298 --> 00:21:46,759
They were then layered through the whole game

383
00:21:47,239 --> 00:21:49,161
to flavor every choice that the player made

384
00:21:49,681 --> 00:21:51,162
as they played through it.

385
00:21:54,300 --> 00:21:58,501
So then our previous recommendations, or our previous stories that were generated,

386
00:21:58,541 --> 00:22:02,662
and the previous feeds that we had, became this one dedicated recommendations feed.

387
00:22:03,782 --> 00:22:07,623
So, we took all of our recommendations and worded them as a BTIT.

388
00:22:07,943 --> 00:22:11,744
That was really important, so if we had an event that was recommended because it was popular,

389
00:22:12,304 --> 00:22:15,545
or because it was a way of pushing the player through the progression...

390
00:22:16,302 --> 00:22:21,086
We reworded them. We took the player that was one above you on the speed wall, which is our

391
00:22:21,106 --> 00:22:26,250
friend's leaderboard, and then we just worded it as, this player is 0.2 seconds ahead of you.

392
00:22:26,890 --> 00:22:34,897
Beat them to take second. And with this, that just meant that every single time we had, even

393
00:22:34,937 --> 00:22:39,881
if we had run out of beat-its of those places where a friend had beaten you, we were able to

394
00:22:41,597 --> 00:22:44,840
give that nudge for competition. We always like to say it's not

395
00:22:44,880 --> 00:22:47,722
really, we don't want to push the player through competition.

396
00:22:47,762 --> 00:22:50,344
We don't want to push the players into rivalry. But it's

397
00:22:50,384 --> 00:22:52,105
more just like the game is there, it's just giving the

398
00:22:52,145 --> 00:22:56,168
player a nudge and being like, you know what, this guy, I'm

399
00:22:56,208 --> 00:23:00,431
just saying, but he's beaten you. And we felt that that was

400
00:23:00,471 --> 00:23:03,774
really working. The other thing we did was we balanced that

401
00:23:03,834 --> 00:23:07,276
signal to noise ratio. So we tuned it back so there were

402
00:23:07,296 --> 00:23:10,078
never more than five cop and five racer recommendations.

403
00:23:12,840 --> 00:23:18,402
And also at that point, for going into production, we recognized from a while back that we wouldn't

404
00:23:18,442 --> 00:23:24,224
be able to make the responsive UX experience that we wanted on a website, especially on

405
00:23:24,504 --> 00:23:25,664
previous generation consoles.

406
00:23:25,704 --> 00:23:28,925
You just needed too much memory to have that sort of web experience.

407
00:23:29,405 --> 00:23:34,927
So we rebuilt our front-end as a web-driven, console-oriented UX.

408
00:23:35,307 --> 00:23:38,468
So that meant it suited up, down, left, right, forward, and back.

409
00:23:42,603 --> 00:23:46,365
So then to really break it down and give those examples,

410
00:23:46,405 --> 00:23:51,006
I'm going to have a look at a session with recommendations

411
00:23:51,226 --> 00:23:53,207
just to talk through what we shipped.

